Determined to reduce poverty and disease in parts of the country, a nongovernmental organisation (NGO), Regional Sustainable Energy Centre for Excellence for Sub Saharan Africa (RSECESSA), said that it would invest about $3 billion grant on water, health, education and entrepreneurship in the 774 local governments in Nigeria. Chairman of RSECESSA, Alhaji Musbahu Mohammed,  who disclosed this at a press conference, in Abuja, said that the four areas of intervention by the organisation, was aimed at reducing poverty, diseases and having a productive population, in line with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) initiatives. Mohammed explained that the strategy would involve the reconstruction of primary and JSS classes in all the LGAs, adding that the intervention is a way of making financial grants available to local governments in a conditional partnership agreement where they contribute three per cent as counterpart contribution for the execution of the project. Also speaking, the executive director of the NGO, Ibrahim Aminu-Trader, explained further that the four areas of interest were carefully selected to reduce poverty, bring healthcare closer to the people, to achieve a productive population. Aminu-Trader added that the grant would also involve providing educational materials to schools, provision of one model science primary school in every LGA, providing school buses, building dispensaries and provision of ambulances, among others.  